WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:05.498
The second thing we're looking at is these binding sites.

00:05.558 --> 00:17.213
Now these are single properties of different amino acids and we're simply looking at all the other tokens that focuses their attention.

00:17.393 --> 00:18.595
Why is this important?

00:18.695 --> 00:26.044
Because these binding sites are central to the structure or to the function of the protein.

00:26.245 --> 00:28.047
If this here is a binding site,

00:28.027 --> 00:31.735
then that's a very central important point of the protein.

00:32.657 --> 00:39.311
So a lot of these other things are going to be determined by what this binding site is.

00:40.072 --> 00:47.588
This binding site needs to have a very particular function and therefore probably needs to be a very particular amino acid.

00:47.568 --> 00:54.478
And the other things here are sort of supporting this binding site because they form the 3D structure around it and so on.

00:54.498 --> 01:01.488
So you would expect a lot of attention to be put on this binding site.

01:01.508 --> 01:02.549
And what do we find?

01:04.011 --> 01:08.277
We find that it's a bit more murky than before.

01:08.257 --> 01:11.984
So, you can see that the attention is kind of spread out.

01:12.485 --> 01:15.530
Percentage of each head's attention that focuses on binding sites.

01:15.971 --> 01:21.922
Especially in the deeper layers, binding sites are targeted at much higher frequency than would occur by chance.

01:22.643 --> 01:26.991
Head 7.1 has the highest percentage, with 34%.

01:27.798 --> 01:39.696
So also here, you can see that it is spread out, but this is because multiple heads are now focusing on these binding sites, because probably binding sites come in different variations.

01:40.076 --> 01:44.764
So you'll have lots of heads specializing on attending to binding sites.

01:45.124 --> 01:48.930
And they say it is much higher frequency than would occur by chance.

01:49.010 --> 01:56.421
And you can see here, this head is the highest with 34% of its attention focused on binding sites.

01:56.401 --> 02:05.373
You can also see the general trend of the attention being rather in the later layers, which we would expect from a tertiary structure.

02:06.094 --> 02:10.019
Now, yeah, it would be interesting here.

02:10.480 --> 02:16.047
Here you also see that actually most of the things are in the last layer.

02:16.027 --> 02:25.025
which points to points to rather maybe lower lower level information, because we reasoned before about the last layer, or I was just wrong.

02:25.365 --> 02:35.385
But also in a general trend, you can see that the attention is rather shifted towards the later layers, because this is sort of a higher order function.

02:37.255 --> 02:37.656
Okay.

02:38.377 --> 02:45.748
If you look at the same calibration experiment, you can see that the picture is not as clear.

02:45.808 --> 02:49.313
There is the general trend at the beginning, but then it sort of flattens out.

02:49.734 --> 02:58.808
So you can sort of differentiate the very probably not a binding site from the somewhat probably a binding site.

02:58.788 --> 03:01.973
but it's not a perfectly calibrated classifier.

03:02.333 --> 03:08.562
And that might just be because there are many things specializing in different types of binding sites.

03:08.842 --> 03:10.905
So you can't just go to this one head.

03:10.945 --> 03:12.828
So this is just for this one head.

03:13.890 --> 03:26.027
You can't just go to that one and expect that to classify all the binding sites because you might want to combine all of the high ranking ones here.

03:27.897 --> 03:29.150
to form a classifier.

